definition.value: A class of diuretics which promote aquaresis (the excretion of water without electrolyte loss).
Primary zwitterion of L-Lysine present at the isoelectric point
A primary ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of 4-aminobenzoic acid resulting from the protonation of the amino group.
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of 4-aminobenzoic acid.
The trialkylammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the amino group of oripavine; Major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide cation that is the conjugate acid of argipressin, arising from the protonation of the N-terminal amino group and the guanidino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A catecholamine in which the aminoethyl side-chain is hydroxy-substituted at C-1 and methylated on nitrogen.
A primary aliphatic ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of desferrioxamine B; major species at pH 7.3.
A diester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy groups of thiomalic acid with ethanol. It is a metabolite of the insecticide malathion.

A member of the class of benzenes that is benzene substituted with one or more alkenyl groups. It is a group of naturally occurring compounds that are synthesized as secondary metabolites in various plants, including nutmeg and basil.

An oil extracted from the germ of Zea mays. Typical fatty acid composition is 52% linoleic acid, 31% oleic acid, 13% palmitic acid, 3% stearic acid, and 1% linolenic acid. It also contains significant amounts of vitamin E.
A substance that increases the rate of a chemical reaction.
An activator of an enzyme-catalysed reaction.
An N-acyl-D-alpha-amino acid anion resulting from deprotonation of both carboxy groups of N-acetyl-D-aspartic acid. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.

An artemisinin derivative that is artemisinin in which the lactone has been converted to the corresponding lactol methyl ether. It is used in combination with lumefantrine as an antimalarial for the treatment of multi-drug resistant strains of falciparum malaria.

A macrolide antibiotic with formula C46H80N2O13. It is used for the treatment of respiratory disease in cattle at high risk of developing bovine respiratory disease associated with Mannheimia haemolytica.

A macrolide antibiotic with formula C40H76N2O12. It is used for the treatment of of bovine respiratory disease caused by Mannheimia haemolytica, Pasteurella multocida, Histophilus somni and Mycoplasma bovis in beef and non-lactating dairy cattle. The compound is also licensed in Europe for the treatment of footrot in sheep caused by Dichelobacter nodosus and Fusobacterium nodosus.
A dipeptide zwitterion resulting from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of aspartame; major species at pH 7.3.
A fatty alcohol consisting of a hydroxy function at any position of an unbranched saturated chain of fourteen carbon atoms.

A member of the class of indazoles that is 1H-indazole substituted by [4-(4-methylpiperazin-1-yl)-2-(tetrahydro-2H-pyran-4-ylamino)benzoyl]amino and 3,5-difluorobenzyl groups at positions 3 and 5, respectively. It is a potent inhibitor of TRKA, TRKB, TRKC, ROS1, and ALK (IC50 values of 0.1 to 1.7 nM), and used for the treatment of NTRK, ROS1 and ALK gene fusion-positive solid tumours.
A fatty alcohol consisting of a hydroxy function at any position of an unbranched saturated chain of thirteen carbon atoms.

A secondary carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (3'S)-2'-oxo-1',2',5,7-tetrahydrospiro[cyclopenta[b]pyridine-6,3'-pyrrolo[2,3-b]pyridine]-3-carboxylic acid with the amino group of (3S,5S,6R)-3-amino-6-methyl-1-(2,2,2-trifluoroethyl)-5-(2,3,6-trifluorophenyl)piperidin-2-one. It is a selective oral, small-molecule antagonist of calcitonin gene-related peptide (CGRP) receptor that has been approved for the treatment of migraine.
An antagonist at any calcitonin gene-related peptide receptor.
A fatty alcohol consisting of a hydroxy function at any position of an unbranched saturated chain of sixteen carbon atoms.
A solvent used in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy.
A fatty alcohol consisting of a hydroxy function at any position of an unbranched saturated chain of eighteen carbon atoms.
A fatty alcohol consisting of a hydroxy function at any position of an unbranched saturated chain of twenty carbon atoms.
Any fatty alcohol which has a chain length greater than C27.
Any fatty alcohol with a chain length between C6 and C12.
A fatty alcohol with a chain length of less than C6.
A fatty alcohol consisting of a hydroxy function at any position of an unbranched saturated chain of twenty-two carbon atoms.
Any 3-oxo steroid that contains a double bond between positions 1 and 2.

An N-glycosyl-1,3,5-triazine that is 4-amino-1,3,5-triazin-2(1H)-one substituted by a beta-D-ribofuranosyl residue via an N-glycosidic linkage. An antineoplastic agent, it is used in the treatment of myeloid leukaemia.

Triamcinolone acetonide with hydrogen instead of the fluorine substituent at position 9. A corticosteroid anti-inflammatory, it is used topically as a cream, ointment or lotion for the treatment of various skin disorders.
Any pyridone that is pyridin-4-one or its derivatives by substitution of one of more of the hydrogens.
A cephalosporin compound having acetoxymethyl and [2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetyl]amino side groups.
A hydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of mesalamine, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.

A 3-oxo-Delta(1),Delta(4)-steroid that is 16beta-methylpregna-1,4-diene-3,20-dione bearing hydroxy groups at the 11beta and 17alpha positions, fluorine at position 9, and a chlorine substituent at position 21. It is used as its 17alpha-propionate ester to treat various skin disorders, including exzema and psoriasis.
A group of heterocyclic compounds based on the 5-methyl-5,6,7,8-tetrahydropteroic acid skeleton conjugated with one or more L-glutamic acid or L-glutamate units.
Any aminopurine having the amino substituent at the 2-position.
Any compound having 6-aminopurine (adenine) as part of its structure.
A mitochondrial respiratory-chain inhibitor that interferes with the action of ATP synthase.
A glycosyl compound arising formally from the elimination of water from a glycosidic hydroxy group and an H atom bound to a carbon atom, thus creating a C-C bond.
A semisynthetic cephamycin antibiotic which, in addition to the methoxy group at the 7alpha position, has 2-thienylacetamido and carbamoyloxymethyl side-groups. It is resistant to beta-lactamase.
The zwitterionic form of loracarbef.
An N-acetyl-amino acid having D-configuration.
